,Recommended,314520,29700867,Posted: 4 February,all,WyattDurp,"I was a little apprehensive buying this game, due to the reviews, but I'm glad I gave it a shot.  Haven't had a single crash or glitch since I've been playing.Overall, this game scratches the fishing sim itch very well. Haven't had this much fun since the original Trophy Bass from Sierra back in the day. The tackle machanics are simple and it's easy to gain the tackle points to unlock the gear you want to specifically target fish. The dynamic weather and changes in fishing pace really add some depth: you're not going to be catching them quickly all the time, and you have to consider what's in your tackle box and your surroundings.Landing a fish is fairly straightforward, and I think that's been my only real disappointment. After a while, the bigger fish will just give up and swim straight to you, so I imagine tweaking the AI would be needed to fix that. Catching a 40lb carp or 60lb catfish should involve more than just holding the rod tip high and keeping the reel button pressed down.Casting seems to be another bone of contention with a lot of folks. Give yourself the time to learn it and it's easy. If you can crank up your mouse sensitivity, it helps a lot. Between the short, flipping casts and the long casts, you can cover any  area you want to near the peg you're fishing.A few tips if you find yourself stuck with some of the common problems:-You can't select a rod, change rig or put your rod down unless you're standing close to the edge of the peg-If progression seems slow, try free fishing at some of the later-stage lakes. The individual fish can make you way more tackle points than a tourney-Casting just takes practice. Don't get frustrated, make sure you're not underneath trees or in an area where you're constantly hitting the opposite bank-This game is somewhat resource intensive, keep that in mind if you're on an older PC. Might need to adjust a few things for smooth framerateIf you're looking for a fishing game, this one is hard to beat currently. It's relaxing, enjoyable and definitely exciting when it needs to be."
