,Not Recommended,314520,13480604,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,dwarf_toss,"I wouldn't buy into this DLC sales platform. It was semi-working as a beta, but in 2017 it is pretty much broken on its best day.The issues are NUMEROUS, the gameplay is inconsistent, and to add insult to injury they have rapid-fire released 2 paid DLCs for what is an objectively broken game! If it were my game, I'd feel like a crook trying to get dev funding on the back of a broken game, but that's me.To the point:- Fights are awful since removing the netting mechanic. Ever since all you really need to do is reel in with low-ish drag so your line never snaps and wait for it to tire so you can reel it in all the way  and press the net button. Even then sometimes it'll get close and the tension will skyrocket for no good reason annnd you lose the fish anyhow.- This game is very poorly optimized. For how it looks in a given setting it should not be so resource-hungry and laggy.These are the 2 biggest ongoing issues for months and months now. At this point it just looks like they're either trying to fund the development needed to fix this broken game (with new DLC), or are trying to make as much cash as they can off of the game before everyone writes it off forever and it dies.Anyhow, I feel like an idiot for endorsing this game and feel like I got suckered by that video of the team talking about how they wanted to make the best fishing game. It's a damn shame, because as you'll see below, the game had extreme potential at one point.Do not buy unless you can get it VERY cheap and don't mind gambling on its future. I just can't see this game recovering after a few years of spinning its wheels and sinking.What follows is the OLD REVIEW I left from December 2014 when the game was in beta and sadly working better than it does in Q3 of 2017:With Phase 6, I think it's even clearer than before that this game is going to turn out to be something good. It started out as a very solid, albeit bare, fishing game, but with every update features are added, and mechanics are dialed in some more. The team seems to be listening intently and working hard to put out as much win in every update as they possibly can.This update brings a working multiplayer mode, which consists of the training lake (only) and up to 4 (iirc) other people fishing. There is a (half-working atm) chat function that lets players on a lake share tips and brag about big catches, which is very cool (if I see someone landing many fish, I tend to ask what bait they're using). Using chat while on a peg is problematic, though, due to the hotkeys for keyboard controls not being disabled while focus is on the chat box. My whole peg has been closed many times because I tried to chat, heh. The chat box also has a bad habit of ignoring sentences. Other than that, multiplayer is definitely working and enjoyable.The quality of the fishing experience gets better with every update (imo), and the team behind it stay on the forums, getting feedback and making changes based on what they see and hear. Force feedback on a 360 controller is much improved, and the controls, for the most part, make sense. However, general consensus is that a mouse gives much better control of power for accurate casting.You carry a tackle box and up to three fishing rods, and gain new gear by spending money earned from catching fish. Lake bed conditions and other factors make the careful choosing of bait and gear an important part of the process, as well as knowing a good spot or two. One can have 3 fishing rods baited and in the water at a time, and alarms on each rod (audible + light) let you know if something is nibbling and running with anything.There are occasional bugs (flying fish, SPOD-arm until restart), but nothing too bad. After the features get hammered out better I am sure that the few there are will be dealt with accordingly.If you like fishing and video games, this is a pretty safe bet. Just don't expect it to be a polished experience at this time."
